The elastic Kubernetes service.

The Kubernetes service runs the Kubernetes control plane, the ay-pee-eye server, the key-value store, the scheduler, and the controllers, as a managed AWS service; you're responsible for the worker nodes, or you use Fargate for a nodeless pattern.

Choose it over the native container service when one of these applies: your team already runs Kubernetes and wants one operational model; multi-cloud portability matters, since Kubernetes manifests are largely cloud-agnostic; you need rich Kubernetes-specific scheduling like taints, tolerations, and custom operators; or you're adopting the broader Kubernetes ecosystem of charts, meshes, and git-ops tools.

Choose the native container service when none of those apply and you want simplicity, lower cost at small scale, and the deepest AWS integration. The Kubernetes control plane carries a small hourly cost per cluster that matters at small scale but disappears at large scale.
